author: Michelle
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 28, 2020
review_content: I'm a banana flavor fan so I thought I'd give this a shot and in my opinion it's one of the better tasting banana yogurts. I'll be buying these again. I do wish the pouches had more in them. These have only 3oz compared to cups that usually have 5 or 6oz. For the record I've never rolled my Jeep nor did I eat cup yogurt while driving. :DI do want to add, these really helped settle my nausea. I have some knee issues and once in a while I'll take a Vicodin I'm prescribed to. When I started to feel nauseous I felt like I had to eat something and this actually settled it quickly. Something to maybe think about if you have to take prescription pain pills you get the nausea side effect.
title: Now I can eat yogurt and drive without rolling my Jeep! :D

author: +or-
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 19, 2020
review_content: There are no live cultures in this product and no reference whatsoever to cultures at all other than it being made of, "Cultured Reduced Fat Milk" as the first ingredient.  I love the GoGo fruit and vegetable products but this one is not worth the purchase.  Thankfully, I only purchased a package of 4 pouches because each of the 4 people who consumed one after refrigeration said they would have rather had a pouch of milk.  I would have rated these as a 2 but everyone else thought they were a 1, so the majority ruled. They were made in France.
title: Sweet and milky

date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 18, 2018

I was a bit skeptical about "shelf stable" yogurt, but I read the packaging MULTIPLE TIMES to ensure I really do not need to refrigerate.My only complaint is the product listing itself -- it very clearly advertises "48 pouches" but this only ships as a single 4-count box. Buyer beware!

author: Kathleen San Martino
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 5, 2019
review_content: There are 60 portable packages of yogurt in six boxes (10 per box) of two flavors (blueberry and berry). There is no need to refrigerate this unless it is opened. Once it is opened it either needs to be consumed right away or put in the fridge for no longer than 24 hours after which time it should thrown away.To consume, just screw off the top and suck up like a straw while squeezing the package into your mouth. It was easiest if I titled my head back to "eat" it. The blueberry does not taste like blueberry to me but just a conglomerate of berries.  The berry flavor tastes mostly like strawberry to me.Each pouch is one serving of 90 calories with 15 from fat, 5% saturated fat, 3% cholesterol, 12g of sugar, and 4g of protein, etc. See photo two for the full nutrition label and ingredients. Cultured reduced fat milk and can sugar are the first two ingredients in each.In summary, this tastes like a sugary milk snack to me and it lacks the beneficial cultures of yogurt. I think this is better than candy but I do not believe this is as healthy as real yogurt. It does taste pretty good and it is smooth and creamy. Also the fruit comes from either blueberry or strawberry/raspberry puree. After having tried this, I would not buy it unless I needed a portable source of milk protein. Also, at the current price of $49.88, it is expensive as it comes to a little more than .83 cents per 3 ounce serving.UPDATE March 9, 2019 - I gave some to my Postman and he really likes these. He said they taste very good to him.UPDATE March 11, 2019 - I gave these to my boyfriend and he said they are "not bad really" but it was "difficult to get past the serving method" (meaning having to sip it up like a straw).
title: Portable, sweet, thick yogurt but without any live & beneficial cultures

review_content: These yogurts are (I guess) meant for kids. At 3 Oz per portion, an adult like me can easily eat 3-4 in a row before feeling satisfied. Therefore easy to keep readily available.- Good ingredients, all natural.- Good portions for small kids.- Pouch can be closed after opening (I am not sure why because it is very small to start with)- Easy to handle.- Good tasteWhat I like less or completely dislike about them:- Not environment friendly. That is a lot of packaging for such a small quantity.- Expensive pouches at almost one dollar per pouch. When compared to any regular yogurt, the price is maybe 3 times more expensive per Oz.- Not frankly suitable for adults.In conclusion:Keeping in mind the clients target (kids),  these pouch are a great addition for any family. The taste and quality is good. As for me, I am always feeling uneasy about them since I cannot satisfy myself with one only and about the environmental impact.3 stars.

author: GardenCat
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 4, 2019
review_content: I didn't try these warm.  I've only had cold ones because that's the only way I eat yogurt.  I'm glad they are shelf stable though because that's a great convenience for storage.These taste ok, but they are like a kid's yogurt in that they are very sweet and the flavors are sweeter and stronger than natural flavors would be.  I was actually very suprised to learn they didn't have HFCS in them.  They are blended, and thick and creamy, but sweeter than the Greek yogurt we usually eat.  Still, we all like these.  The only problem any of us has with them is that they only contain 3 ounces of yogurt and we'd prefer twice that.  They even have a lid that screws back on, in case you want to save the rest, which we find strange.  I think the packaging is a bit much- it seems like they put more thought and effort into it than they did how much yogurt someone might want- this is only going to satisfy kids under 6 or 7, I think.It might be that they were thinking they were making a toddler product, but many older kids and adults will like this too.The pouches fit well in just a clear plastic bin in the fridge.  The boxes they come in are not that big, but they are a bit hard to get into when on a shelf.
title: Thick, sweet, tastes like yogurt, but there's not enough in a pouch for older kids/adults

author: Jerry P. Danzig
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2019
review_content: This store-at-room-temperature yogurt tastes great, and I appreciate the convenience of not having to keep it refrigerated, but the packaging needs work for several reasons:1) Each "pouch" gives you too small a serving size. Is this product designed just for kids? I think the serving size needs to be bigger, even for kids.2) Too much plastic -- each pouch has a plastic twist-off top designed to allow you to refrigerate the unused portion of a pouch, but who isn't going to suck the contents of a pouch down at one brief sitting? So the manufacturer should lose the environmentally unfriendly twist tops and just give each pouch a standard tear-off top.3) Plastic toothpaste-tube-style dispenser hole a turn-off. Again, squeezing a normal foil pouch would probably dispense the product without the need for utensils just as well.4) Even the box containing the pouches has an odd opening perforation that needs to be re-thought.Finally, these little suckers are EXPENSIVE. A little less than a buck a pop for each tiny serving.So I give a thumbs-up to the yogurt itself, but the price and packaging both need serious revision.
title: Too Much Package, Too Little Product

author: Anonymous
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 20, 2019
review_content: I pulled one of these right out of the box after being delivered as it is winter and still pretty cold outside so I figured it would be pretty close to what it would taste like being pulled out of a packed lunch.  The texture of this was creamy and thick with a mild blueberry flavor.  I did notice an funky sort of aftertaste, a little bit bitter and not quite something I could put my finger on; if I had to guess I would think it is just the ultra pasteurization process and the change it has on the milk's overall flavor.  Personally, I didn't love squeezing this product out, I would have rather spooned it into my mouth but I can see the appeal of it being less messy for kids.  The convenience of these is great but there sure is a lot of waste that isn't easily recyclable.  I'm not so sure all children will love the thick texture of this product so I'd recommend finding a smaller package first before committing to the large quantity that this ships in.  I really like most of their flavored applesauce and like that this company has healthy snacks that taste good and you can feel good about sharing with your children but this is one product I wouldn't purchase again for myself.

author: Wendy
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 25, 2019
review_content: Using protein powder while traveling is easy - mix with water and you're done.  Not the tastiest, though, especially if adding supplement capsules which can throw off the taste.  At home, I add a whole banana and 2 or 3 ice cubes to sweeten and make the protein 'shake' a bit richer, blending with a hand blender.  That is not practical when traveling, however.  I tried doing the shake in a hand shaker, but uh, no.  Got it down, but with the vitamin supplements added - not pleasant!  I got online and found these Gogo Squeez yogurt pouches in banana flavor and scooted to the grocery to get some.  Added it to my next morning's protein shake and YUM!  Success!  MUCH more palatable, and some extra protein to boot.The only cons:  Packaging does not list potassium content or whether live yogurt cultures are present (I would guess not, considering the shelf-stable packaging).  But for my purposes, this was a good fit and will be again when traveling and wanting to keep life simple!
title: Perfect for Smoothies While Traveling

author: Quoad Toad
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 8, 2019
review_content: If you're someone who is never hungry, these little GoGo pouches are great.  Perhaps you're going through extreme stress, a loss, or an illness.  I have tried several flavors and find them to be an easy way to get some nutrition.  First, you don't have to actually see what you're eating.  Sometimes just the sight of food makes me feel nauseous.  With these pouches, I don't have to see the food.  The pouches are small, so it doesn't feel like as much of a chore to eat.  The flavor is OK.  It's not as good as other yogurt brands, but sometimes the sight or smell of yogurt in the little cups makes me nauseous.I feel wasteful using this product.  There is so much packaging and it seems wasteful that there is so much packaging for relatively little food inside.  On the other hand, these GoGo pouches have gotten me through some difficult times where I just couldn't eat normally.
title: Good way to eat when you're not hungry

author: N. B. Kennedy
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 20, 2019
review_content: "Heat treated after culturing." That wording is required of manufacturers who treat products with heat to lengthen their shelf life. The heat kills off the live cultures in yogurt, so how is this product even called yogurt? Our child did have yogurt in their lunch for years in elementary school. I know commercial yogurts have a lot of sugar, and this one is no exception (12g per pouch), so I shouldn't have allowed it. But... with kids, it's all about what they'll eat, not what they should eat. Looking at the ingredients, there is good and bad. The sugar, while high, isn't high fructose corn syrup; it's cane sugar. Protein of 4g per serving is good. The flavor (blueberry) is acceptable, although our child always preferred raspberry. The 3-ounce size of the pouch is good for a snack, but wouldn't be enough for a full lunch. I just don't like all the plastic packaging, but what can you do?
title: Okay taste, but is it yogurt?

review_content: The "GoGo squeeZ Yogurtz Yogurt" is an interesting idea.  It puts yogurt in a small tube which does not have to be refrigerated.  However, there are drawbacks.
